cv_info.projects:
PROJECTS 
 
Context: Visual analytics project (Distinction) 
Nov 2021 - Jan 2022 
 
• 
I had to apply a Visualization analytics framework using visual analytical tools onto a complex dataset to produce 
sophisticated visualizations that are open to human interaction which can uncover meaningful findings.  
• 
I Investigated the competition between ride-sharing app companies Uber and Lyft using real-time data of customers' trips 
in Boston through visualizations and a soundproof data science methodology. I further formed research questions by 
dataset features and researching the companies utilizing taxi industry domain knowledge to help assess the competition 
through KPIs like location, distance, and time.  
• 
I produced 10+ visualizations including line graphs, bar-chart and heat-maps plots of Uber and Lyft and their KPI, using 
Tableau and Python. I applied a regression model to see if ride fare prices can be predicted based on factors like distance 
and service type, e.g., ride for up to 4 compared to ride for 6+ passengers. 
• 
I found that Uber had marginally outperformed Lyft in every location. Lyft was competitive at shorter distances, but Uber 
outperformed on distance journeys above 6 kilometres, this was reflected in the regression model as the price was 
predicted more easily on rides with shorter distances. I also noticed that Uber charges less for their premium car services 
and more for regular services when compared to Lyft. 
Context: Machine learning project (Distinction)                                                                              Nov 2021 - Dec 2021  
• 
I was asked to train and optimise two supervised or two unsupervised machine learning models to then evaluate each 
algorithm based on performance metrics like accuracy and then present my work through a presentation.  
• 
I applied two supervised machine learning models Naïve Bayes and Logistic regression to classify if a patient has 
coronary heart disease from a dataset containing patient records from a Cleveland hospital using MATLAB and Microsoft 
PowerPoint.   
• 
I performed explanatory data analysis of the dataset and then split the dataset into a training and test set, and for a 
validation set, I perform cross-validation on the training set. I further optimised my models through feature selection and 
hyperparameter tuning through Bayesian optimisation to get the best fit and optimal model.  
• 
Both models performed well with Logistic regression performing at 86.5% accuracy whilst naïve Bayes performed at 
86.
